      • matches

        public BuiltQuery matches(java.lang.String key,
                 java.lang.String regex,
                 java.lang.String modifiers)
        Add a regular expression constraint for finding string values that match the provided regular expression. This may be slow for large datasets.
        Parameters:
        key - The key to be constrained.
        regex - The regular expression pattern to match.
        modifiers - Any of the following supported Regular expression modifiers.
      • use i for case-insensitive matching.
      • use m for making dot match newlines.
      • use x for ignoring whitespace in regex
        • Returns:
        BuiltQuery object, so you can chain this call.

        Example :
              // 'blt5d4sample2633b' is a dummy Application API key
      BuiltApplication builtApplication  = Built.application(context, "blt5d4sample2633b");
      BuiltClass  bugsClass = builtApplication.classWithUid("bugs");
      BuiltQuery bugsQuery = bugsClass.query();

      bugsQuery.matches("name", "^browser", "i");

      • notInQuery

        public BuiltQuery notInQuery(java.lang.String key,
                    BuiltQuery builtQueryObject)
        Add a constraint to fetch all objects that do not contains given value against specified reference key.
        Parameters:
        key - the key of the referred object.
        builtQueryObject - The query to perform on the this BuiltQuery object.
        Returns:
        BuiltQuery object, so you can chain this call.

        Note: :- This will fetch objects for a class by querying the fields in the referred object. Use notinQuery if you want to fetch objects that do not match the conditions specified (negation of inQuery). Can be used for nested references.(referred object inside referred object and so on).



        Example ;
              // 'blt5d4sample2633b' is a dummy Application API key
      BuiltApplication builtApplication  = Built.application(context, "blt5d4sample2633b");

      BuiltClass   projectClass = builtApplication.classWithUid("project");
      BuiltQuery projectQuery = projectClass.query();

      BuiltClass   bugClass = app.classWithUid("bug");
      BuiltQuery bugQuery = bugClass.query();

      projectQuery.where("name", "Super Project #41");

      bugQuery.notInQuery("project", builtQuery1);

      • or

        public BuiltQuery or(java.util.ArrayList<BuiltQuery> queryObjects)
        Add a constraint to fetch all objects which satisfy any queries.
        Parameters:
        queryObjects - list of BuiltQuery instances on which OR query executes.
        Returns:
        BuiltQuery object, so you can chain this call.

        Example :
              // 'blt5d4sample2633b' is a dummy Application API key
      BuiltApplication builtApplication  = Built.application(context, "blt5d4sample2633b");
      BuiltClass   projectClass = builtApplication.classWithUid("project");
      BuiltQuery projectQuery = projectClass.query();

      BuiltQuery query = projectClass.query();
      query.where('username','something');

      BuiltQuery subQuery = projectClass.query();
      subQuery.where('email_address','something@email.com');

      ArrayList<BuiltQuery> array = new ArrayList<BuiltQuery>();
      array.add(builtQuery1);
      array.add(builtQuery2);
        
      projectQuery.or(array);

      • customQuery

        public BuiltQuery customQuery(java.util.HashMap<java.lang.String,java.lang.Object> custom)
        To construct complex queries.
        Parameters:
        custom - HashMap object.
        Returns:
        BuiltQuery object, so you can chain this call.

        Note: If a complex query needs to be performed and if it is difficult to specify it using the BuiltQuery methods, a HashMap can be provided that specifies all the conditions.
        The HashMap should be as per the JSON format specified in the REST API docs .



        Example :
              // 'blt5d4sample2633b' is a dummy Application API key
      BuiltApplication builtApplication  = Built.application(context, "blt5d4sample2633b");

      BuiltQuery projectQuery = projectClass.query();
        
      HashMap<String, Object> customQuery = new HashMap<String, Object>();
      customQuery.put("query_param_key","query_param_value");
        
      projectQuery.customQuery(customQuery);

        public BuiltQuery select(java.lang.String whereKey,
                BuiltQuery builtQueryObject,
                java.lang.String pickedKey)
        Add a constraint to the query that requires a particular key's object to be equal to the provided object.
        Parameters:
        whereKey - The key to be constrained.

        pickedKey - the key for which the values should be returned after executing select query.

      bugQuery.select("project", selectQuery, "name");

      • nearLocation

        public BuiltQuery nearLocation(java.lang.Object locationObject,
                      int radius)
        Add a constraint to fetch all objects near specified location, search for objects within specified radius.
        Parameters:
        locationObject - either BuiltLocation instance or object uid in string. In latter case, it will use the object's location.
        radius - radius in meters.
        Returns:
        BuiltQuery object, so you can chain this call.

        Example :
               // 'blt5d4sample2633b' is a dummy Application API key
      BuiltApplication builtApplication  = Built.application(context, "blt5d4sample2633b");
      BuiltClass   personClass = builtApplication.classWithUid("person");
      BuiltQuery personQuery = personClass.query();
        

      BuiltLocation locationObj = new BuiltLocation();
      locationObj.setLocation(19.4667, 72.872);

      personQuery.nearLocation(locationObj, 1000);

      • withInLocation

        public BuiltQuery withInLocation(java.util.ArrayList<java.lang.Object> locationObjectList)
        Add a constraint to fetch all objects within specified points.
        Parameters:
        locationObjectList - ArrayList of location objects. Location object can be either BuiltLocation instance or object uid in string. In latter case, it will use the object's location. At least three objects have to be specified in order to form the simplest polygon.
        Returns:
        BuiltQuery object, so you can chain this call.

        Example :
               // 'blt5d4sample2633b' is a dummy Application API key
      BuiltApplication builtApplication  = Built.application(context, "blt5d4sample2633b");
      BuiltClass   personClass = builtApplication.classWithUid("person");
      BuiltQuery personQuery = personClass.query();
        

      BuiltLocation locationObj1    = new BuiltLocation();
      locationObj1.setLocation(19.4667, 72.872);
        
      BuiltLocation locationObj2    = new BuiltLocation();
      locationObj2.setLocation(19.4667, 72.872);
        

      ArrayList<Object> locationList = new ArrayList<Object>();
        
      locationList.add(locationObj1);
      locationList.add(locationObj2);

      personQuery.withInLocation(locationList);
